Detection of Impending Heart Attack
The system uses a trained ML model (running on each node or a local gateway) to recognise pre‑attack patterns:

ST‑segment elevation / depression

Sudden HRV drop

abnormal QRS complexes

When a high‑risk pattern is detected, the person’s chest node immediately broadcasts a “cardiac alert” packet to all authorised peers.

Peer Heart – Simultaneous Action
The alert is received by the other person’s chest node (and optionally their VR headset). The receiving node can:

Sound an audible alarm through the VR headset speakers.

Display a full‑screen visual warning in the VR environment (e.g., “John’s heart is at risk – call 911”).

Activate a vibration/haptic pattern on the recipient’s wrist node to get immediate attention.

Because the communication is simultaneous (latency < 100 ms typical), the second person can react in real‑time – calling emergency services or administering first aid – while the first person may already be incapacitated.

EEG/VR Role
The VR headset provides a high‑immersion interface: a virtual “heart monitor” that shows the peer’s real‑time ECG.

EEG sensors (head nodes) can detect if the wearer is conscious and paying attention; the system can escalate alerts if no response is seen.

In a clinical research setting, both persons can be in the same VR environment, seeing each other’s vital signs superimposed on their view.

